private <T> Set<T> executeWithQueuesLocked(final Supplier<Set<T>> action) {
    tasksAndActionsLock.lock();           // Lock 1
    restoredActiveTasksLock.lock();       // Lock 2 (nested)
    exceptionsAndFailedTasksLock.lock();  // Lock 3 (nested)
    try {
        return action.get();
    } finally {
        exceptionsAndFailedTasksLock.unlock();
        restoredActiveTasksLock.unlock();
        tasksAndActionsLock.unlock();
    }
}
```

**Deadlock Risk:** Lock ordering is consistent (Lock1→Lock2→Lock3 always), so deadlock is unlikely, BUT this method is called from `tasks()` (line 1048), `restoresActiveTasks()` (line 1053), `activeTasks()` (line 1059), and `standbyTasks()` (line 1066). These are called from external code paths that may hold other locks.

